@NODE Introduction
@TITLE "statline · Introduction"


    @{b}Introduction@{ub}


    statline is a small utility which can show different
    status information about your MorphOS system. The
    output format is highly configurable. 

    statline can be used as Commandline tool, but also has 
    a nice MUI GUI to use it as compensation for the missing 
    information in Ambient titlebar.

    

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements
@TITLE "statline · Requirements"


    @{b}Requirements@{ub}


    - MorphOS 1.4

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation
@TITLE "statline · Installation"


    @{b}Installation@{ub}


    Copy statline to a place you like. Probably you want
    to copy it to WBStartup, but then don't forget to copy
    this very guide to SYS:Help to keep it available 
    (you'll need it).

    When you want to use statline also as shell command then
    don't forget to add "WBStartup" to the system path.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Startup
@TITLE "statline · Startup"


    @{b}Startup@{ub}

    
    You can start statline from Ambient or from the
    CLI.
 

    @{b}Ambient@{ub}

    No special options or tooltpyes are required. It
    still supports all default MUI- and Commodity-
    tooltypes.

    When you install statline to WBStartup then you
    might want to add the DONOTWAIT tooltype.


    @{b}CLI@{ub}

    When invoking statline from the Shell then certain
    options are required. Please refer to the @{" CLI options " link Commandline }
    section of this guide.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Commandline
@TITLE "statline · Commandline"


    @{b}CLI options@{ub}


    commandline template:
    TEMPLATE/A,MF=MEMFORMAT,TS=THOUSANDSEPERATOR/S,
    F=FRACTION/S,SL=SIZELETTER/S



    @{b}Description@{ub}


    TEMPLATE/A (required)

        passes a string to statline which can contain
        various placeholders. staltine will immediately output
        this string, but all placeholders will be replaced by
        certain values.

        see: @{" FormatString " link FormatString }
 
        e.g.: morphos:> statline "Available memory: %ma"
              Available memory: 234124456
              morphos:>


    MF=MEMFORMAT (optional)

        Defines size of memory placeholders output.

        possible options:
            GB : g, gb, gigabyte, gbyte
            MB : m, mb, megabyte, mbyte
            KB : k, kb, kilobyte, kbyte
            B  : b, byte

        Byte option is default.

        e.g.: morphos:> statline "Available memory in MB: %ma" MF mbyte
              Available memory in MB: 234
              morphos:>


    TS=THOUSANDSEPERATOR/S (optional)

        Adds thousand seperator to memory output.

        e.g.: morphos:> statline "Available memory: %ma" TS
              Available memory: 234.124.456
              morphos:>


    F=FRACTION/S (optional)

        Adds fraction part to memory output when memory
        format is gigabyte, megabyte or kilobyte.

        e.g.: morphos:> statline "Available memory in MB: %ma" MF="MegaByte" F
              Available memory in MB: 234,1
              morphos:>


    SL=SIZELETTER/S (optional)

        Adds describing letter behind memory output.

        e.g.: morphos:> statline "Available memory : %ma" MF=M F SL
              Available memory : 234,1M
              morphos:>

@ENDNODE



@NODE MainWindow
@TITLE "statline · Main window"


    @{b}Main window@{ub}


    The main window is divided in 3 parts: left there's a
    hideable dragbar, a textfield in the center and a hideable
    sizegadget on the right side.

    On first startup you probably have to resize the window to
    see anything in the textfield.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MenuOptions
@TITLE "statline · Menuoptions"


    @{b}Menu options@{ub}


    @{b}Project@{ub}

        About...

            Opens the About window with copyright information and
            credits.

        About MUI...

            Opens MUIs About window.

        Iconify

            Iconifies statline.

        Quit

            Quits statline immediatelly.


    @{b}Settings:@{ub}

        Prefs...

            Opens Preferences. Most settings are very
            similiar to the available commandline options, so
            please refer the @{" CLI options " link Commandline }.

            In addition you can set certain options for
            the GUI, like visibility of drag- and sizegadget
            and uptime interval.

        Load last saved

            Loads last saved configuration.

        Save

            Saves current settings to disk.

        Snapshot

            Snapshots statlines main window position
            and size.

        Unsnapshot

            Unsnapshots position and size.

        MUI...

            Opens MUI Settings.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FormatString
@TITLE "statline · FormatString"


    @{b}FormatString@{ub}


    The formatstring can contain following special placeholders. The
    output can be futher formated using escape sequences.


    additional formating:

        %\\          -  line feed
        %[          -  ESC

        see: @{" MUI escape sequences " link ESCMUI           } and
             @{" CON escape sequences " link ESCCON           }

        %%          -  %


    memory (only fast):

        (use the capital placeholders for output in '%')

        %m, %ma,
        %M, %MA     -  available memory
        %ml, %ML    -  largest free block
        %mm, %MM    -  maximal memory (abox)
        %mt, %MT    -  total amount of memory
        %mu, %MU    -  used memory

        %mc         -  number of memory chunks


    exec:

        %ed         -  devices
        %el         -  libraries
        %ep         -  ports
        %er         -  resources


    tasks:

        %t          -  number of tasks
        %tr         -  running tasks
        %ts         -  sleeping tasks

        %~          -  context switches
        %~v         -  voluntary context switches
        %~i         -  involuntary context switches
        %~s         -  contect switches per second


    load and cpu usage:

        %c          -  cpu usage (in %)
        %C          -  cpu usage with active dnetc filter (in %)

        %l1         -  load average for past 1 minute
        %l2         -  load average for past 5 minutes
        %l3         -  load average for past 15 minutes


    intuition

        %is         -  open screens
        %iw         -  open windows


    static system information:

        %?, %?n     -  system identifier
        %?p         -  CPU
        %?c         -  cpu clock (in MHz)
        %?b         -  bus clock (in MHz)
        %?m         -  machine type

        %°          -  prints CPU Temperature in °C (this is not
                       tested at all and will probably work only
                       with PPC750 (G3) and a MorphOS > 1.4.x)


    miscellaneous

        %v[<var>]   - prints out environment variable <var>, e.g.
                      %v[HOSTNAME]

        %u          - system uptime in minutes
        %U          - system uptime in "Dd, HH:MM:SS" format
        %ur         - record system uptime in minutes
        %UR         - record system uptime in "Dd, HH:MM:SS" format

        (please note: the record uptime is saved each 60th update
        of statline. That means when you have a update intervall of
        1s (default) it is saved each minute once. If you have a
        update intervall of 2s then it's only saved each 2 minutes.
        Statline also first starts saving the record uptime when
        you're going to make a new record (if your current uptime
        is less than the record uptime then nothin will be saved at
        all))


    @{b}TIP:@{ub} when you use cpu usage with dnetctaskfilter or the 'environment
         variable' placeholder, then you should add "statline" to
         the ignore filter in SnoopDOS, else it wil spam your
         SnoopDOS.log. :)

@ENDNODE

@NODE ESCMUI
@TITLE "statline · Escape sequences: MUI"


    @{b}Escape sequences: MUI@{ub}


    Following sequences and formating options are only
    in GUI mode available.

    (btw: for %[ you also can enter a real ESC, but using the
    placeholder is more easy.)


	%[-         -  disables the mui text engine for all following
                       characters. so following options will not
                       be processed after this sequence.

	%[u         -  soft style: underline

	%[b         -  soft style: bold

	%[i         -  soft style: italic

	%[n         -  resets soft style to normal.

	%[<n>       -  use pen number n (2..9) as front pen for following
                       output.

                       e.g.: " %[3 coloured text whoohoo! %[0 "

	%[c         -  centers current and following line(s) (does only
                       work on string start or after a %\\ )

	%[r         -  same but right justify

	%[l         -  same but left justify

	%[I[<s>]    -  add MUI image with specification <s> (see below).



    @{b}MUI Images@{ub}

    MUI has a very powerful formating engine. Since the statline GUI uses
    MUI we can use all advantages of this, e.g. we can add external images
    to the output string, think about: instead of writing "memory:" you
    add a small ramdisk.png. Very cool IMHO. :)


        %[I[0:<x>]  - use mui builtin pattern (this has maybe no effect
                      after all! :).

                      e.g.: " %[I[0:3] "


        %[I[1:<x>]  - use mui builtin standard image.

                      e.g.: " %[I[1:6] "


        %[I[2:<rgb>]

                    - adds some coloured box, useful as spacer object.

                      e.g.: " %[I[2:FF00FF]


        %[I[3:<n>]  - <n> is a string (name of an external boopsi
                      image class). defaul search path is
                      mossys:prefs/muigfx/

                      e.g.: " %[I[3:xen/scrollbars/xenbar.image] "


	%[I[4:<n>]  - <n> is a external MUI brush (.mbr, .mf#?)

                      e.g.: " %[I[4:xen/Plain/13pt/ArrowUp.mf0] "


        %[I[5:<n>]  - <n> is a external picture (very useful option,
                      but choose small images (relative to font size),
                      else you'll have ugly scaling)

	              e.g.: " %[I[5:ram:littlepicture.png] "


                      Tip: when u need little icons with Alphashadows
                           then rename the png files to .mbr and use
                           the %[I[4:<n>] escape sequence to add it.


        %[I[6:<n>]  - <n> is pre configured mui image/ background.

                      e.g.: " %[I[6:22] "


        %[I[7:<rgb>|<rgb>]

                    - adds a gradient box, useful as spacer object.

                      e.g.: " %[I[7:FFFFFF|000000]


@ENDNODE

@NODE ESCCON
@TITLE "statline · Escape sequences: CON"


    @{b}Escape sequences: CON@{ub}


    Following sequences and formating options are only
    in commandline mode available.


        *E[<n>;<r>;<g>;<b>V

                    - sets certain systempen to specific
                      color.

                      e.g.: " *E[1;255;0;0V some red text"


    (more escape sequences are explained in amigados manual)

@ENDNODE

@NODE FAQ
@TITLE "statline · FAQ"


    @{b}Frequently Asked Question@{ub}


    Q: I configured statline, but on next start all settings are
       back to default. What's wrong?

    A: Don't forget to save the settings with "Save" in the "Settings"
       menu.


    Q: When I restart staline it opens only a very small window, why
       that?

    A: Don't forget to snapshot the window with the "Snapshot"
       function you'll find in "Settings" menu.


    Q: Can you add feature <x>?

    A: Maybe.


    Q: Can you add some Taskbar features and possibilities to start
       programs?

    A: No, i don't want to add such things. Statline is only supposed
       to display (statistical) information about your system. 
    

@ENDNODE

@NODE bugs
@TITLE "statline · Known Bugs"


    @{b}Known Bugs@{ub}


    - statline opens only a very small window on first
      startup, solution: resize manually and snapshot the
      window.

    - PowerPC 7457 is not detected: it displays as 7447. But
      since no MorphOS system uses the 7457 yet this probably
      does not matter. :)


@ENDNODE

